prs.tagLine: Apartments to Rent
prs.location:
Griffith Wood’s location on the longest tree-lined avenue in the Northern Hemisphere is as suited for commuting to and from the city centre as it is for enjoying relaxed suburban living. 

Griffith Wood is located on the prestigious Griffith Avenue, Dublin 9. While quiet and peaceful, the community is a vibrant one that’s well populated by local shops, schools, parks and recreational sporting facilities. All of which are just minutes away and can be reached on foot. 

The complex is also close to Dublin City Centre, Dublin City University, Fairview Park, Croke Park, the International Financial Services Centre (IFSC) and East Point Business Park, and is well serviced by bus and cycle routes. The DART line in Clontarf is a short walk away, while Dublin City Airport and the M1 and M50 motorways can be easily accessed, allowing you to explore Dublin, the counties of Ireland and further afield.

prs.location:
Brickfield Square is ideally located in Dublin 12, right on the doorstep of the dynamic and ever-evolving Dublin 8 neighbourhoods, including Inchicore and Rialto. These areas are quickly becoming some of Dublin’s most exciting cultural and residential hubs. 

Just minutes away, Inchicore has been named one of the 50 coolest neighbourhoods in the world by TimeOut (2025), celebrated for its authentic charm, creative scene, and strong community vibe. Nearby Rialto offers vibrant cafes, independent shops, and quick access to the Museum of Modern Art (IMMA) and the expanses of Phoenix Park.

Living at Brickfield Square means enjoying the calm and comfort of a well-established community with easy access to all the excitement and convenience of the inner city. You’re just 3km from the city centre, with Ashleaf Shopping Centre only 3.1km away and St. Stephen’s Green just 3.6km from your door. 

Shopping and Dining: 
Brickfield Square offers access to a wide range of shopping and dining options from independent eateries to larger retail destinations. Enjoy local cafes, bakeries, and restaurants just a short walk or cycle away, or head to Ashleaf Shopping Centre for convenient grocery shopping and retail outlets. The city centre is just a few Luas stops away for even more dining and shopping choices.

Transport Information from Brickfield Square: 
Brickfield Square is extremely well-connected by public transport, making travel to and from the city centre, Docklands, or greater Dublin fast and efficient.

Luas
The Suir Road Luas stop on the Red Line is approximately a 10-minute walk from Brickfield Square. It provides quick, direct access to the city centre and beyond making commuting easy and reliable.

Bus Services
A number of Dublin Bus routes service the area, including routes 13, 18, 27, 56A, 77A, and 151. These provide excellent connections across the city, ensuring you're always well linked whether you're headed to work, college, or weekend plans.

Road Access
Brickfield Square offers excellent road connectivity, with nearby access to the N7 and M50. Whether you're commuting by car or heading out of the city for the weekend, these major routes make travel simple and convenient.

prs.tagLine: Stunning Brand New
prs.location:
Bluebell is a Dublin city suburb situated approximately 6 km south-west of the city centre adjacent to the Camac River. The suburb borders the Grand Canal and Inchicore to the north, Walkinstown 
to the south, Drimagh to the east and Kylemore to the West. The development is accessed via Muirfield Drive and is nestled adjacent to the extensive Lansdowne Valley Park and Pitch & Putt Course and the historic Drimnagh Castle. Both Lansdowne Valley Park and Drimnagh Castle are protected conservation areas.


The location is excellently served by a number of public transport facilities with the Bluebell LUAS 
stop within walking distance 300 m north east on the Naas Road, providing convenient access to St. 
James’s Hospital (approximately 10 minutes) and the city centre (approximately 20 minutes).
The Naas Road also provides a Quality Bus Corridor (Dublin 
Bus routes 13, 68 & 69) adding to the accessibility of the area to the city centre and beyond.This location is a convenient gateway to all the 
facilities and amenities that the city has to offer including museums, galleries, shops, places of work 
and leisure.


The immediate area benefits from an established local community that offers all of the amenities 
one would expect, such as shops, cafés, bars, supermarkets, retail parks and recreational amenities
The surrounding area was designated within the ‘Naas Road Lands Local Area Plan’ noting that there 
is a great opportunity for future regeneration and improved integration of the area into the emerging 
fabric of the capital city.
